</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>Letter requesting information on the reported placement of the Dutch tradition of 
</p>
<p>Sinterklaas and Black Pete on the National Inventory of Intangible Cultural Heritage. 
</p>
<p>According to the information received, on 15 January 2015, the Dutch Centre for Folk 
</p>
<p>Culture and Intangible Heritage, a Government-funded organization, placed the Dutch 
</p>
<p>traditional Sinterklaas and Black Pete festival on the National Inventory of Intangible 
</p>
<p>Cultural Heritage. Allegedly, concerned communities, who find the tradition of Black 
</p>
<p>Pete to be offensive, as it perpetuates a negative stereotyped representation of African 
</p>
<p>people and people of African descent, were not informed nor consulted about this 
</p>
<p>process. A previous communication on the same subject was sent on 17 January 2013, 
</p>
<p>see A/HRC/23/51, case no. NLD 1/2013. 
</p>
